Description: SchoolSpeak is a web service for elementary, middle and preschools bringing all solutions the school community need under a single login.
Full Description: SchoolSpeak was started by parents in technology industry and educators. It started as an initiative to reduce paper used in schools and make communication and engaging with the school community more efficient. They looked at various programs and decided to create a solution that best fit the needs of elementary, middle and pre schools where parental involvement is high. Schools have been using many different web solutions. Some addressed one or few areas very well. Some were very difficult to administer, costly or did not exactly solve the problem. Quite a few were designed for high schools or universities and did not fit well with preschools, elementary and middle schools. And there were a number of free services that parents managed such as email groups, which many times school administrators did not have control or access. Their mission is to bring all web solutions required for schools under a single umbrella - an extranet for schools. While working with schools, they discovered that a number of tasks can be easily automated using web tools. SchoolSpeak is a work in progress. They partner with schools in developing new solutions.

Description: Thinking Machines Corporation provides advanced data mining software for predicting customer behaviors.
Headquarters Regions: Greater Boston Area, East Coast, New England
Full Description: Thinking Machines Corporation is a supercomputer manufacturer. It provides advanced data mining software for predicting customer behaviors. The company produced a number of Connection Machine models: the CM-1, CM-2, CM-200, CM-5, and CM-5E. The CM-1 and 2 came first in models with 64K (65,536) bit-serial processors (16 processors per chip) and later, the smaller 16K and 4K configurations. The Connection Machine was programmed in a variety of specialized languages including Lisp, CM Lisp, C, and CM FORTRAN. These languages used proprietary compilers to translate codes into the parallel instruction set of the Connection Machine. The CM-1 through CM-200 were examples of SIMD architecture (Single Instruction Multiple Data), while the later CM-5 and CM-5E were MIMD (Multiple Instructions Multiple Data) that combined commodity SPARC processors and proprietary vector processors. Thinking Machines Corporation also introduced an early commercial RAID2 disk array, the DataVault, circa 1988. Founded in 1983, Thinking Machines Corporation is based in Burlington, Massachusetts.
